| Config | `references/config.md` | Config, Config.schema, Redacted |
| Streams | `references/streams.md` | Stream (minor v4 changes) |
| Migration | `references/migration.md` | v3→v4 rename table, import map |

## v4 Import Map

| v3 Package | v4 Import |
|------------|-----------|
| `@effect/platform` (HttpClient, etc.) | `effect/unstable/http` |
| `@effect/platform` (HttpApi, etc.) | `effect/unstable/httpapi` |
| `@effect/rpc` | `effect/unstable/rpc` |
| `@effect/cli` | `effect/unstable/cli` |
| `@effect/sql` | `effect/unstable/sql` |
| `@effect/cluster` | `effect/unstable/cluster` |
| `@effect/ai` | `effect/unstable/ai` |
| `@effect/platform-bun` | `@effect/platform-bun` (still separate) |
| `@effect/platform-node` | `@effect/platform-node` (still separate) |
| `@effect/vitest` | `@effect/vitest` (still separate) |

## Pre-Implementation (mandatory)

Before writing Effect v4 code:

1. **Read types** — find relevant Context.Service, TaggedErrorClass, Schema classes
2. **Check import paths** — v4 uses `effect/unstable/*` for platform/rpc/cli
3. **Read sibling code** — match existing patterns
4. **Check migration** — `references/migration.md` for v3→v4 renames

## Core Rules

### 1. Always `Effect.fn` — never `function x() { return Effect.gen(...) }`

Same as v3. `Effect.fn` is unchanged in v4.

```typescript
// BAD
export function getUser(id: string) {
  return Effect.gen(function* () { ... })
}

// GOOD
export const getUser = Effect.fn("getUser")(function* (id: string) {
  const db = yield* Database
  return yield* db.findUser(id)
})
```

### 2. `Context.Service` is canonical — NOT `Effect.Service`

```typescript
import { Context } from "effect"

// BAD
class MyService extends Effect.Service<MyService>()("MyService", { ... }) {}

// GOOD — function style
const Database = Context.Service<{ query: (sql: string) => string }>("Database")

// GOOD — class style
class Database extends Context.Service<Database, {
  readonly query: (sql: string) => Effect.Effect<string, DbError>
}>()("Database") {
  static layer = Layer.effect(Database, ...)
  static layerTest = Layer.succeed(Database, ...)
}
```

### 3. Services for everything side-effectful

Same as v3. No free-floating effectful functions.

### 4. Bubble service requirements up

Same as v3. Don't provide layers deep inside.

### 5. Never pass context as parameters — yield it

Don't thread services/refs through function arguments. Yield them from context directly and let requirements bubble through the type system.

```typescript
// BAD — threading context as parameters
const processOrder = Effect.fn("processOrder")(function* (
  order: Order,
  db: DatabaseService,    // ← passing context as param
  logger: LoggerService,  // ← passing context as param
) {
  yield* logger.info(`Processing ${order.id}`)
  yield* db.save(order)
})

// caller has to manually thread services
const program = Effect.fn("program")(function* () {
  const db = yield* Database
  const logger = yield* Logger
  yield* processOrder(order, db, logger)
})

// GOOD — yield context directly, requirements bubble
const processOrder = Effect.fn("processOrder")(function* (order: Order) {
  const db = yield* Database
  const logger = yield* Logger
  yield* logger.info(`Processing ${order.id}`)
  yield* db.save(order)
})

// caller just calls — no threading
const program = Effect.fn("program")(function* () {
  yield* processOrder(order)
})
```

This applies to any yieldable context: services, refs, config, etc. If you can `yield*` it, don't pass it.

### 6. Never raw errors — always tagged

```typescript
// v4: Schema.TaggedErrorClass (renamed from TaggedError)
export class NotFound extends Schema.TaggedErrorClass<NotFound>()(
  "NotFound",
  { id: Schema.String }
) {}
```

### 7. Never standalone exported functions with side effects

Same as v3. Wrap in services with static `layer`/`layerTest`.

### 8. Never try/catch in Effect generators

The `@effect/language-service` flags `tryCatchInEffectGen`. Use `Effect.try` or `Effect.tryPromise` instead.

```typescript
// BAD
const load = Effect.fn("load")(function* () {
  try {
    const data = yield* Effect.promise(() => file.text())
    return JSON.parse(data)
  } catch {
    return defaultValue
  }
})

// GOOD
const load = Effect.fn("load")(function* () {
  const data = yield* Effect.promise(() => file.text())
  return yield* Effect.try({
    try: () => JSON.parse(data) as unknown,
    catch: () => new ParseError({ message: "invalid json" }),
  })
})
```

### 9. Never JSON.parse/JSON.stringify — use Schema

The LSP flags `preferSchemaOverJson`. Use `Schema.fromJsonString` for type-safe JSON parsing/encoding.

```typescript
// BAD
const data = JSON.parse(text) as MyType

// GOOD
const MySchema = Schema.Struct({ name: Schema.String, count: Schema.Number })
const decode = Schema.decodeUnknownEffect(Schema.fromJsonString(MySchema))
const encode = Schema.encodeEffect(Schema.fromJsonString(MySchema))

const data = yield* decode(text)                    // string → MyType
const json = yield* encode(data)                    // MyType → string
```

### 10. No unnecessary Effect.gen

The LSP flags `unnecessaryEffectGen` for generators with a single yield/return. Flatten these.

```typescript
// BAD — single yield, unnecessary gen
const getName = (id: string) =>
  Effect.gen(function* () {
    yield* recorder.record({ service: "User", method: "getName", args: { id } })
  })

// GOOD — direct call
const getName = (id: string) =>
  recorder.record({ service: "User", method: "getName", args: { id } })

// BAD — single yield + return
const getCount = () =>
  Effect.gen(function* () {
    yield* recorder.record({ service: "Counter", method: "get" })
    return 42
  })

// GOOD — pipe with Effect.as
const getCount = () =>
  recorder.record({ service: "Counter", method: "get" }).pipe(Effect.as(42))
```

### 11. No pointless wrapper functions

If a function just delegates to a single effect call without adding logic, don't create the function — use the effect directly at the call site.

```typescript
// BAD — wrapper adds nothing
const getUser = (id: string) => userService.findUser(id)
const deleteAll = () => repository.clear()

// GOOD — call the effect directly where you need it
yield* userService.findUser(id)
yield* repository.clear()

// OK — wrapper adds real value (transforms, combines, or adds context)
const getActiveUser = (id: string) =>
  userService.findUser(id).pipe(Effect.filterOrFail(
    (u) => u.active,
    () => new InactiveUser({ id })
  ))
```

### 12. Deterministic service keys

  1	import { Schema } from 'effect';
  2	import { nanoid } from 'nanoid';
  3	
  4	/**
  5	 * The CMS content model (CMS plan §"Content schema", decisions D2 / D5).
  6	 *
  7	 * One bilingual `SiteContent` document is the single source of truth for every
  8	 * editable piece of the site — the three conferences (2024 / 2025 / 2026), the
  9	 * team, and the ~200 UI translation keys. It is decoded at the boundary by the
 10	 * `Content` service (C3) and authored / published by the `/admin` editor (C5).
 11	 *
 12	 * Modelling principles (see `~/.brain/principles`):
 13	 *   - `make-impossible-states-unrepresentable`: every bilingual field is `Text`
 14	 *     (both locales required, both non-empty); a Conference whose pricing is
 15	 *     undecided carries `registration: Option.none()` rather than empty tuples;
 16	 *     an `accentColor` is a validated `#rrggbb` string, never an arbitrary one.
 17	 *   - `boundary-discipline`: `AssetKey` rejects anything that is not a plain
 18	 *     in-bucket object key (no leading `/`, no URL scheme, no `..` traversal),
 19	 *     so a hand-edited document can never smuggle in a path that escapes the
 20	 *     bucket or points at an absolute URL.
 21	 *   - `use-the-platform`: dates are stored as ISO-8601 `YYYY-MM-DD` strings; the
 22	 *     `Content` boundary (C3) converts them to the existing `[start, end]`
 23	 *     millisecond tuples so route / component code is untouched.
 24	 *
 25	 * The encoded form of this schema IS the JSON stored at `content/site.json`, so
 26	 * every field round-trips losslessly through `encode → JSON → decode` (proven by
 27	 * the C2 round-trip test).
 28	 */
 29	
 30	// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
 31	// Primitives
 32	// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
 33	
 34	/** A bilingual string: both locales required and non-empty. */
 35	export const Text = Schema.Struct({
 36	  en: Schema.NonEmptyString,
 37	  fr: Schema.NonEmptyString,
 38	});
 39	export type Text = typeof Text.Type;
 40	
 41	/**
 42	 * A bucket object key (e.g. `2024/speakers/matt.png`). Validated so that a
 43	 * hand-edited document cannot point outside the bucket or at an absolute URL
 44	 * (`boundary-discipline`). The key must be a watertight boundary because C5
 45	 * serves it via `GET /images/*`, where a permissive URL router could
 46	 * percent-decode a smuggled `%2e%2e` back into `..` after this check ran — so
 47	 * the validator forbids the encoding forms outright rather than only the
 48	 * literal ones:
 49	 *   - non-empty;
 50	 *   - no leading `/` (keys are bucket-relative, not absolute paths);
 51	 *   - no URL scheme (`http:`, `data:`, …);
 52	 *   - no backslash `\` (a Windows / alt path separator that segment-splitting on
 53	 *     `/` would not catch, e.g. `a\..\b`);
 54	 *   - no percent sign `%` (so no percent-encoded separator or dot can hide a
 55	 *     `%2e%2e` / `%2f` traversal that a downstream decode would re-materialise —
 56	 *     legitimate in-bucket keys are plain ASCII paths and never need encoding);
 57	 *   - no empty / `.` / `..` path segments (no traversal, no double slashes).
 58	 */
 59	const assetKeyFilter = Schema.makeFilter<string>(
 60	  (key) => {
 61	    if (key.startsWith('/')) return 'AssetKey must not start with "/"';
 62	    if (/^[a-z][a-z0-9+.-]*:/i.test(key)) {
 63	      return 'AssetKey must not contain a URL scheme';
 64	    }
 65	    if (key.includes('\\')) {
 66	      return 'AssetKey must not contain a backslash';
 67	    }
 68	    if (key.includes('%')) {
 69	      return 'AssetKey must not contain a percent-encoded character';
 70	    }
 71	    const segments = key.split('/');
 72	    if (segments.some((seg) => seg === '' || seg === '.' || seg === '..')) {
 73	      return 'AssetKey must not contain empty, "." or ".." segments';
 74	    }
 75	    return undefined;
 76	  },
 77	  { title: 'AssetKey' },
 78	);
 79	
 80	export const AssetKey = Schema.NonEmptyString.check(assetKeyFilter).pipe(
 81	  Schema.brand('AssetKey'),
 82	);
 83	export type AssetKey = typeof AssetKey.Type;
 84	
 85	/**
 86	 * A bilingual pair of bucket keys: the same asset cropped/authored once per
 87	 * locale. Most images are locale-neutral and carry a single `AssetKey`, but the
 88	 * hero artwork is genuinely per-locale today — the source files diverge by
 89	 * locale (e.g. `2025/en/hero-desktop.jpg` *and* `2025/fr/hero-desktop.jpg` are
 90	 * two distinct files on disk, likewise `2026/{en,fr}/hero-desktop.png`).
 91	 * Modelling the key as `{ en, fr }` (mirroring `Text`) keeps both locales'
 92	 * exact paths representable so the rendered `src` survives the boundary
 93	 * untouched (`make-impossible-states-unrepresentable`); a single `AssetKey`
 94	 * here would silently drop one locale's art.
 95	 */
 96	export const LocalizedAssetKey = Schema.Struct({
 97	  en: AssetKey,
 98	  fr: AssetKey,
 99	});
100	export type LocalizedAssetKey = typeof LocalizedAssetKey.Type;
101	
102	/** A reference to an image stored in the bucket, with bilingual alt text. */
103	export const ImageRef = Schema.Struct({
104	  key: AssetKey,
105	  alt: Text,
106	});
107	export type ImageRef = typeof ImageRef.Type;
108	
109	/**
110	 * A single accent colour as a `#rrggbb` hex string (CMS decision D5 — replaces
111	 * today's misnamed `Conference.theme`, which was the accent colour, not the
112	 * theme name).
113	 */
114	export const HexColour = Schema.NonEmptyString.check(
115	  Schema.isPattern(/^#[0-9a-fA-F]{6}$/, { title: 'HexColour' }),
116	).pipe(Schema.brand('HexColour'));
117	export type HexColour = typeof HexColour.Type;
118	
119	/**
120	 * An external `https://` URL safe to interpolate into an `href` or an iframe
121	 * `src` from hand-edited document content (registration-launch Branch 3, settled
122	 * #4). The `registrationUrl` / `scheduleUrl` / map-embed fields are author-set
123	 * strings that the rendered detail page feeds straight into a link/iframe, so the
124	 * brand must be a watertight XSS boundary — modelled per-component on
125	 * `assetKeyFilter` above, **parsing the URL and inspecting its components**, NOT
126	 * a substring or `origin` test (an `origin` check excludes the path, so it would
127	 * admit `https://www.google.com/anything`).
128	 *
129	 * The filter rejects, by parsing:
130	 *   - a value that is not a parseable absolute URL (relative refs, garbage);
131	 *   - any protocol other than `https:` (so `javascript:`, `data:`, `http:`,
132	 *     `file:` etc. can never reach an `href`/`src`);
133	 *   - embedded credentials (`username` / `password` non-empty), so a smuggled
134	 *     `https://user:pass@evil/` cannot ride along.
135	 * The brand keeps the guarantee load-bearing past the decoder: a raw `string` is
136	 * not an `ExternalHttpsUrl` until it has crossed the schema
137	 * (`boundary-discipline`, `make-impossible-states-unrepresentable`).
138	 */
139	const parseUrl = (value: string): URL | undefined => {
140	  try {
141	    return new URL(value);
142	  } catch {
143	    return undefined;
144	  }
145	};
146	
147	const externalHttpsUrlFilter = Schema.makeFilter<string>(
148	  (value) => {
149	    const url = parseUrl(value);
150	    if (url === undefined) return 'ExternalHttpsUrl must be a valid absolute URL';
151	    if (url.protocol !== 'https:') {
152	      return 'ExternalHttpsUrl must use the https: protocol';
153	    }
154	    if (url.username !== '' || url.password !== '') {
155	      return 'ExternalHttpsUrl must not contain embedded credentials';
156	    }
157	    return undefined;
158	  },
159	  { title: 'ExternalHttpsUrl' },
160	);
161	
162	export const ExternalHttpsUrl = Schema.NonEmptyString.check(
163	  externalHttpsUrlFilter,
164	).pipe(Schema.brand('ExternalHttpsUrl'));
165	export type ExternalHttpsUrl = typeof ExternalHttpsUrl.Type;
166	
167	/**
168	 * A Google Maps **embed** URL safe to use as an iframe `src` (registration-launch
169	 * Branch 3). It is an `ExternalHttpsUrl` (https-only, no credentials) PLUS a
170	 * per-component check that the URL **parses** to the Google Maps embed endpoint:
171	 * `host === 'www.google.com'` AND `pathname.startsWith('/maps/embed')`. This is
172	 * deliberately a host+path check, **not** an `origin` check: `origin` excludes
173	 * the path, so an origin test would admit `https://www.google.com/anything`,
174	 * which is not an embed and could be an arbitrary Google page. Constraining the
175	 * iframe source to the embed endpoint prevents an arbitrary-iframe XSS through a
176	 * hand-edited `mapEmbedUrl` (settled #4, modelled on `assetKeyFilter`).
177	 */
178	const googleMapsEmbedUrlFilter = Schema.makeFilter<string>(
179	  (value) => {
180	    const url = parseUrl(value);
181	    if (url === undefined) {
182	      return 'GoogleMapsEmbedUrl must be a valid absolute URL';
183	    }
184	    if (url.host !== 'www.google.com') {
185	      return 'GoogleMapsEmbedUrl host must be www.google.com';
186	    }
187	    if (!url.pathname.startsWith('/maps/embed')) {
188	      return 'GoogleMapsEmbedUrl path must start with /maps/embed';
189	    }
190	    return undefined;
191	  },
192	  { title: 'GoogleMapsEmbedUrl' },
193	);
194	
195	export const GoogleMapsEmbedUrl = Schema.NonEmptyString.check(
196	  externalHttpsUrlFilter,
